J. B. Rainsberger wrote:

&gt; I have been working with Dave Astels very loosely on the question of how
&gt; the vocabulary of testing affects the way we write programs. He wants to
&gt; see what happens if we remove the vocabulary of testing, hence his
&gt; &quot;Behavior-Driven Development&quot;. I don&#39;t like the name, but I don&#39;t have a
&gt; better alternative, so I&#39;m living with it. Dave has started with RSpec
&gt; (for Ruby) which feels a lot like xUnit, but doesn&#39;t use the language of
&gt; testing. I have just started working towards JSpec, using Joe Walnes&#39;
&gt; brilliant observation as a springboard.

I&#39;m intrigued and confused.  Infused?  Contrigued?  That&#39;s it, contrigued.

If I write this, how far am I from Astel&#39;s ideas?

@RunWith(Behavior.class)
public class LoginBehavior {
    @Story public void shouldAllowCorrectLoginToEnter()

    @Story public void shouldForbidIncorrectLoginFromEntering()

    @Story public void shouldShutDownAccountAfterThreeUnsuccessfulTries()
}

These days, I would write:

public class LoginHandlesCommonCases {
    @Test public void allowsCorrectLoginToEnter()

    @Test public void forbidsIncorrectLoginFromEntering()

    @Test public void shutsDownAccountAfterThreeUnsuccessfulTries()
}

(Side note: interestingly, @Before and @BeforeClass still make sense for 
@Story&#39;s, but @BeforeTest and @BeforeSuite are clumsier in that context.)

    David Saff
